'''Matthew "Matt" Andrew Geary Freese''' (born September 2, 1998) is an American professional [[Association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Major League Soccer]] club [[New York City FC]] and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]].

==Youth career==
Born in [[Wayne, Pennsylvania|Wayne]], [[Pennsylvania]], Freese went through the [[Philadelphia Union]] youth academy before appearing on the bench with Union reserve side, [[Philadelphia Union II|Bethlehem Steel]], during the 2017 season. Not long after, Freese enrolled at [[Harvard University|Harvard]] and played [[College soccer in the United States|college soccer]] for the [[Harvard Crimson men's soccer|Harvard Crimson]], where his older brother Jack rowed heavyweight [[Rowing (sport)|crew]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gocrimson.com/sports/msoc/2018-19/bios/freese_matt_qgni?view=bio|title=Matt Freese|website=Harvard|access-date=March 12, 2019|archive-date=January 13, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220113004132/https://gocrimson.com/404-1.aspx?url=url%3D%2Fcustompages%2Fmsoc%2F2018-19%2Fbios%2Ffreese_matt_qgni%3Fview%3Dbio|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=mlssoccer |title=How Matt Freese charted a breakout path at New York City FC {{!}} MLSSoccer.com |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/matt-freese-s-path-to-new-york-city-fc-breakout-patience-family-more |access-date=2025-01-05 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Jack Freese - 2012-13 - Men's Heavyweight Rowing |url=https://gocrimson.com/sports/mens-heavyweight-rowing/roster/jack-freese/3290 |access-date=2025-01-05 |website=Harvard University |language=en}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Philadelphia Union===
On December 21, 2018, it was announced that Freese would leave Harvard early and join [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Philadelphia Union]] at the beginning of their 2019 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philadelphiaunion.com/post/2018/12/21/philadelphia-union-sign-matt-freese-homegrown-deal|title=Philadelphia Union sign Matt Freese to homegrown deal &#124; Philadelphia Union}}</ref>

Freese made his professional debut on April 19, 2019, coming on as a 54th-minute substitute for [[Andre Blake]] in a 3–0 home win against the Montreal Impact.

On November 8, 2020, Freese made his lone start of the [[2020 Major League Soccer season|2020 season]] against the [[New England Revolution]] on MLS Decision Day. He made one save and kept a clean sheet as the Union clinched their first trophy in club history, the [[Supporters' Shield]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2020-11-08-philadelphia-union-vs-new-england-revolution/recap|title=Recap: Philadelphia Union vs. New England Revolution 11/08/2020 &#124; Matchcenter}}</ref>

===New York City FC===
On January 27, 2023, Freese was traded to [[New York City FC]] in exchange for a guaranteed $350,000 of General Allocation Money, with a possibility of an additional $400,000, as well as a percentage of a future transfer fee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/nycfc-land-goalkeeper-matt-freese-in-trade-with-philadelphia-union|title=NYCFC land goalkeeper Matt Freese in trade with Philadelphia Union &#124; MLSSoccer.com|website=mlssoccer|accessdate=January 27, 2023}}</ref> On December 27, 2024, Freese was named New York City FC's MVP (Most Valuable Player) for the 2024 season after finishing third in the [[Major League Soccer|MLS]] in saves and fourth in save percentage.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |date=2024-12-27 |title=Matt Freese named New York City FC's 2024 MVP |url=https://www.hudsonriverblue.com/matt-freese-named-2024-mvp-new-york-city-fc-mls/ |access-date=2025-01-05 |website=Hudson River Blue |language=en}}</ref> This marked the first time since 2021 that New York City FC gave out the award.<ref name=":0" />

==International career==
[[File:Matt Freese USMNT v Portugal Mar 31 2026-109.jpg |thumb|upright|Matt Freese with the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]] in 2025]]

=== Youth ===
Freese has represented the United States at the U-19 and U-23 levels. Freese was named to the final 20-player [[United States men's national under-23 soccer team|United States under-23]] roster for the [[2020 CONCACAF Men's Olympic Qualifying Championship]] in March 2021.<ref>{{cite web |title=U.S. Under-23 Men's National Team Head Coach Jason Kreis Names Roster for Concacaf Men's Olympic Qualifying Championship |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2021/03/us-u23-mnt-head-coach-jason-kreis-names-roster-for--concacaf-mens-olympic-qualifying-championship |website=www.ussoccer.com |date=March 11, 2021}}</ref>

=== Senior ===
On January 6, 2025, Freese was called up to the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]] by head coach [[Mauricio Pochettino]] ahead of the January camp in Florida, with friendlies against [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]] and [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]]. Freese did not play in either game.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hudson River |first1=Blue Staff |title=Matt Freese called up to US Men's National Team |url=https://www.hudsonriverblue.com/finally-matt-freese-called-up-to-us-mens-national-team/ |access-date=6 January 2024 |work=Hudson River Blue}}</ref>

On May 22, 2025, Freese was again called up by Pochettino to the national team for training camp in [[Chicago]] ahead of matches against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=May 22, 2025 |title=Pochettino Names 27-Player Roster for Training Camp ahead of June Matches Against Turkey and Switzerland |url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2025/05/mauricio-pochettino-27-player-roster-training-camp-june-matches-turkey-switzerland |access-date=May 22, 2025 |website=[[United States Soccer Federation]]}}</ref>

On June 5, 2025, Freese was included in the final 26-player roster for the 2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup. He played in every match of the tournament, keeping 2 clean sheets in the group stage and conceding a total of 6 goals across the competition.

On May 26, 2026, Freese was named to the United States roster for 2026 FIFA World Cup.

==Personal life==
Freese's paternal grandparents, [[Ernst Freese|Ernst]] and Elisabeth Freese, were German scientists who immigrated to the U.S. after World War II and worked for the National Institutes of Health. Freese's father, Andrew Freese, was a neurosurgeon who earned a Ph.D. in neurobiology from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. 

After taking leave from Harvard to join Philadelphia Union, Freese completed his course work online during the COVID pandemic and graduated from Harvard in 2022. <ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/sports/soccer/matt-freese-harvard-usmnt-fifa-world-cup-rcna345907</ref>

